The Smithsonian Institution is constructing the [[National Museum of African American History and Culture]] on a {{convert|5|acre|ha}} site between the grounds of the Washington Monument and the National Museum of American History.  The boundaries of the museum site are Constitution Avenue on the north, Madison Drive on the south, 14th Street NW on the east, and 15th Street NW on the west.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nmaahc.si.edu/section/about_us/view/63 |title=Building Design Update: Building the National Museum of African American History and Culture|publisher=[[National Museum of African American History and Culture]]|accessdate=2010-03-17}}</ref> The museum's [[groundbreaking]] ceremony took place on February 22, 2012.<ref>(1) {{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Patricia|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/23/arts/design/groundbreaking-for-the-museum-of-african-american-history.html|title=Making Way for a Dream in the Nation's Capital|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2012-02-22|accessdate=2012-02-22}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Trescott|first= Jacqueline|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/african-american-museum-groundbreaking-showcases-living-history/2012/02/21/gIQAQGafTR_story.html|title=African American museum groundbreaking showcases living history|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2012-02-22|accessdate=2012-02-23}}</ref>

The population of American elm trees planted on the Mall and its surrounding areas in accordance with the McMillan Plan has remained intact for the past 70 years because of disease management and immediate tree replacement.  [[Dutch elm disease]] (DED) first appeared on the Mall during the 1950s and reached a peak in the 1970s. The NPS has used a number of methods to control this [[fungus|fungal]] epidemic, including [[sanitation]],  [[pruning]], injecting trees with [[fungicide]], replanting with DED-resistant American elm [[cultivar]]s and combatting the disease's local insect [[Vector (epidemiology)|vector]], the smaller European elm [[bark beetle]] ([[Scolytus]] multistriatus), by trapping and by spraying with [[insecticide]]s. [[Soil compaction]] and root damage by crowds and construction projects also adversely affect the elms.<ref>{{cite book|last=Sherald|first=James L|url=http://www.nps.gov/nationalmallplan/Documents/Studies/ElmsoftheMonuCore_HistandMgmtPlan_122009.pdf|title=Elms for the Monumental Core: History and Management Plan|id=Natural Resource Report NPS/NCR/NRR--2009/001|place=Washington, D.C.|publisher=Center for Urban Ecology, National Capital Region, [[National Park Service]]|date=December 2009|accessdate=2010-10-14}}</ref>

[[File:Washington, D.C. - 2007 aerial view.jpg|thumb|275px|2007 aerial view of [[Capitol Hill, Washington, D.C.|Capitol Hill]] and the National Mall, facing west]]

==Other attractions nearby==
{{See also|Category:Visitor attractions in Washington, D.C.}}

Other attractions within walking distance of the National Mall proper include the [[Library of Congress]] and the [[United States Supreme Court Building]] east of the Capitol; the [[White House]] (on a line directly north of the Washington Monument), the [[National Archives and Records Administration|National Archives]], the [[Freedom Forum]]'s [[Newseum]], the [[Old Post Office Pavilion]], the [[National Theatre (Washington, D.C.)|National Theatre]], [[Ford's Theatre]], and the [[Albert Einstein Memorial]] to the north; the [[National Postal Museum]] and [[Union Station (Washington, D.C.)|Union Station]] to the northeast; and the Jefferson Memorial, the [[Franklin Delano Roosevelt Memorial]], the [[Martin Luther King, Jr. Memorial]], the [[George Mason Memorial]], the [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]], and the [[Bureau of Engraving and Printing]] to the south.

==Usage==
The National Mall, in combination with the other attractions in the [[Washington Metropolitan Area]], makes the nation's capital city one of the most popular tourist destinations in the country.  However, it has uses other than as a tourist focal point.

[[File:View of Crowd at 1963 March on Washington.jpg|thumb|left|287px|The 1963 [[March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom]] on the National Mall facing east from the Lincoln Memorial]]

===Protests and rallies===
{{See also|List of protest marches on Washington, D.C.}}

The National Mall's status as a wide, open expanse at the heart of the capital makes it an attractive site for protests and rallies of all types.  One notable example is the 1963 [[March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom]], a [[Demonstration (people)|political rally]] for [[African American]] [[African-American Civil Rights Movement (1955–1968)|civil rights]], at which [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]] gave his famous "[[I Have a Dream]]" speech.

The largest officially recorded rally was the [[Moratorium to End the War in Vietnam|Vietnam War Moratorium Rally]] on October 15, 1969. However, in 1995, the NPS issued a crowd estimate for the [[Million Man March]] with which an organizer of the event, [[Nation of Islam]] leader [[Louis Farrakhan]], disagreed.<ref name=Leef>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Leef|last2=Melillo|first2=Wendy|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/21925324.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Oct+13%2C+1996&author=Leef+Smith%3BWendy+Melillo&desc=If+It%27s+Crowd+Size+You+Want%2C+Park+Service+Says+Count+It+Out%3B+Congress+Told+Agency+to+Stop%2C+Official+Says|title=If It's Crowd Size You Want, Park Service Says Count It Out; Congress Told Agency to Stop, Official Says|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|page=A.34|date=1996-10-13|accessdate=2010-11-29}}</ref>  The next year, a committee of the [[104th United States Congress]] provided no funds for NPS crowd counting activities in Washington, D.C. when it prepared legislation making 1997 appropriations for the [[U.S. Department of the Interior]].<ref name=Leef /><ref>{{cite web|last=Regula|first=Ralph, Committee on Appropriations|url=http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=104_cong_reports&docid=f:hr625.104.pdf|title=House of Representatives Report 104-625:  Department of the Interior and Related Agencies Appropriations Bill, 1997, to accompany H.R. 3662|page=28|quote=The Committee has provided no funding for crowd counting activities associated with gatherings held on federal property in Washington, D.C. If event organizers wish to have an estimate on the number of people participating in their event, then those organizers should hire a private sector firm to conduct the count.|date=1996-06-18|accessdate=2010-11-30}}. Note: The Department of the Interior and Related Agencies Appropriations Bill, 1997 (H.R. 3662), was incorporated into the {{cite web|url=http://www.ustreas.gov/offices/enforcement/ofac/legal/statutes/pl104_208.pdf|title=Omnibus Consolidated Appropriations Act, 1997 (Public Law 104-208, Sept. 30, 1996)}}, at 110 STAT. 3009-181.</ref> {{As of|2009}}, the NPS had not provided any further official crowd estimates for Mall events.<ref>{{cite web|last=Starr|first=Penny|url=http://www.cnsnews.com/news/article/54017|title=Crowd Sizes on National Mall A Matter of Media Speculation|work=[http://www.cnsnews.com/static/about_us CNSNews.com]|publisher=[[Cybercast News Service]]|date=2009-09-14|accessdate=2010-11-30}}</ref>

On April 25, 2004, the [[March for Women's Lives]] filled the Mall.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Abortion activists on the march |date=2004-04-26| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/3657527.stm |accessdate=2009-06-08| publisher=BBC}}</ref>  On January 27, 2007, tens of thousands of protesters [[Opposition to the Iraq War|opposed to the Iraq War]] converged on the Mall (see: [[January 27, 2007 anti-war protest]]), drawing comparisons by participants to the [[Vietnam War]] protest.<ref>(1) {{cite news |first=Ian|last=Urbina |title=Wide opposition to war energizes protests / Washington: Jane Fonda among celebrity protesters joining veterans, politicians in calling for end to war|publisher = San Francisco Chronicle|date=2007-01-28|url =http://sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/01/28/MNGASNQDO81.DTL|accessdate = 2007-01-28 }}<br>(2) {{cite news |first=Ian|last=Urbina | title = Protest Focuses on Iraq Troop Increase | publisher = [[The New York Times]] | date = 2007-01-28 | url = http://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/28/washington/28protest.html?hp&ex=1170046800&en=defcbb536a8a2453&ei=5094&partner=homepage | accessdate = 2007-01-28 }}<br>(3) {{cite news |first=Deborah|last=Charles | title = Tens of thousands demand U.S. get out of Iraq | publisher =[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]| date = 2007-01-28 | url = http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2007/1/28/worldupdates/2007-01-28T093422Z_01_NOOTR_RTRJONC_0_-285278-1&sec=Worldupdates | accessdate = 2007-01-28 }}</ref>{{clear left}}

===Presidential inaugurations===
[[File:Obama inaugural address.jpg|thumb|350px|[[First inauguration of Barack Obama]] on January 20, 2009 facing west from the Capitol]]
{{Main|United States presidential inauguration}}

During [[United States presidential inauguration|presidential inauguration]]s, people without official tickets gather at the National Mall.  Normally, the Mall between [[7th Street (Washington, D.C.)|7th]] and 14th Streets NW is used as a staging ground for the parade.<ref>{{cite news |first=Nikita|last=Stewart|title=Entire Mall To Be Open To Public |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/12/04/AR2008120403719.html?hpid=topnews |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2008-12-05|accessdate=2008-12-05}}</ref>  On December 4, 2008, the Presidential Inaugural Committee (see [[United States presidential inauguration#Organizers]]) announced that "for the first time, the entire length of the National Mall will be opened to the public so that more people than ever before will be able to witness the swearing-in of the [[President of the United States|President]] from a vantage point in sight of the Capitol."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://replay.waybackmachine.org/20081207144648/http://www.pic2009.org/pressroom/entry/open_inauguration/ |title=National Mall Will Be Open to the Public on Inauguration Day|accessdate=2011-03-14|date=2008-12-04 |archivedate=2008-12-07}}</ref> The Committee made this arrangement because of the massive attendance – projected to be as many as 2 million people – that it expected for the [[first inauguration of Barack Obama]] on January 20, 2009. Despite the arrangement, a throng of people seeking access to the event climbed and then removed temporary protective fences around the Smithsonian's Mary Livingston Ripley Garden, six blocks from the site at which Obama took his inaugural oath. Hordes then trampled the garden's vegetation and elevated plant beds when entering and leaving the event.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/25/AR2009032500925.html|title=For Smithsonian, a Sad Souvenir of the Inauguration |date=2009-03-26 |accessdate=2010-03-23|last=Higgins|first=Adrian|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]] |page=H.1}}</ref> Others could not find a way to enter the Mall in time to view the ceremony.  More than a thousand people with tickets missed the event while being stranded in the [[Interstate 395 (District of Columbia-Virginia)#Washington, D.C.|I-395 Third Street Tunnel]] beneath the Mall after police directed them there (see [[Purple Tunnel of Doom]]).<ref>(1) {{cite news |title=Ticket and Travel Troubles Cloud Inauguration Success |date=2009-01-22 |accessdate=2009-01-22|last=Constable |first=Pamela; Sheridan, Mary Beth |work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]] |page=A01 |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/01/21/AR2009012104248.html?sid=ST2009012003386&s_pos= }}<br>(2) {{cite news|url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local-beat/Surviving-the-Purple-Tunnel-of-Doom.html|title=Surviving the Purple Tunnel of Doom: Ticketed paradegoers stranded in tunnel|date=2009-01-21|publisher=NBC Washington|accessdate=2010-03-01}}<br>(3) Coordinates of Third Street Tunnel: {{Coord|38.8897468|-77.0143747|region:US-DC_type:landmark|name=I-395 Third Street Tunnel}}</ref> The [[United States Congress Joint Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies|Joint Congressional Committee on Inaugural Ceremonies]] subsequently announced that ticket holders that were not admitted would receive copies of the swearing-in invitation and program, photos of [[Barack Obama|Obama]] and Vice President [[Joe Biden]], and a color print of the ceremony.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcwashington.com/news/local/No-Consolation-Blocked-Ticket-Holders-Get-Parting-Gifts.html|title=No Consolation: Parting gifts for blocked ticket holders|last=Stabley|first=Matthew|date=2009-01-29|publisher=NBC Washington|accessdate=2009-04-16}}</ref>

===Other events and recreational activities===
The National Mall has long served as a spot for jogging, picnics, and light recreation for the [[Demographics of Washington, D.C.|Washington population]].  The Smithsonian Carousel, located on the Mall in front of the Arts and Industry Building, is a popular attraction that operates seasonally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.si.edu/guides/english.htm|title=Welcome to the Smithsonian|accessdate=2010-01-22|date=August 2006|publisher=Smithsonian Institution}}</ref>  The [[carousel]] was built by the Allan Herschell Company and arrived at [[Gwynn Oak Park]] near [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], in 1947. It was moved to the Mall in 1981.<ref name="Smithsonian carousel" /><ref name=nathan /><ref>Nathan, Amy. Round and Round Together, pp. 3, 15-19, 220-224</ref>

[[File:Fourth of July fireworks behind the Washington Monument, 1986.jpg|thumb|210px|left|Independence Day fireworks display between the Washington Monument and the Lincoln Memorial, July 4, 1986]]

====Annual events====
A number of large free events recur annually on the Mall.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=http://traveltips.usatoday.com/activities-national-mall-washington-dc-105342.html|archivedate=2014-03-30|url=http://traveltips.usatoday.com/activities-national-mall-washington-dc-105342.html|title=Activities at the National Mall in Washington, D.C.|first=Jane|last=Gosford|work=[http://www.usatoday.com/travel/ Travel]|publisher=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=2014-03-30}}</ref> A [[kite]] festival, formerly named the "Smithsonian Kite Festival" and now named the "[[Blossom Kite Festival]]", usually takes place each year on the Washington Monument grounds during the last weekend of March as part of the [[National Cherry Blossom Festival]]. The 2015 kite festival took place on the grounds of the Washington Monunument on March 28.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6X573mxxg|archivedate=2015-03-16|url=http://www.nationalcherryblossomfestival.org/blossom-kite-festival-3/|title=Blossom Kite Festival: March 28, 2015|work=[http://www.nationalcherryblossomfestival.org/about/ National Cherry Blossom Festival]|accessdate=2015-03-16}}</ref>

An [[Earth Day]] celebration often takes place on the Mall around April 22.<ref>(1) {{cite news|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6OSxKGCTK|archivedate=2014-03-30|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/apr/23/news/mn-22596|title=Thousands at National Mall for Earth Day|date=2000-04-23|first=Matea|last=Gold|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=2014-03-30}}<br>(2) {{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/story/2008/04/20/ST2008042002453.html|title=Raining on Her Own Parade: Earth Day Festival 'Great' Despite Mother Nature's Whims|last=Strauss|first=Valerie|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|publisher=[http://www.washingtonpost.com The Washington Post Company, Washington, D.C.]|page=B.1|date=2008-04-21|accessdate=2010-02-25}}<br>(3)  {{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/04/19/AR2009041902087.html|last=du Lac|first=J. Freedom|title=Talking a Green Streak: Music & Antics Lift Earth Day Concert, but Too Much Hot Air Drains Energy From Its Message|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|publisher=[http://www.washingtonpost.com The Washington Post Company, Washington, D.C.]|date=2009-04-20|accessdate=2010-02-25}}<br>(4) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6OSv9OXCM|archivedate=2014-03-30|url=http://yosemite.epa.gov/opa/admpress.nsf/0/030e4694b4a5074d85257870005554b0?OpenDocument|title=APRIL 16-17: Join EPA for Earth Day on the National Mall|date=2011-04-12|work=[http://www2.epa.gov/newsroom Newsroom]|publisher=[[United States Environmental Protection Agency]]|accessdate=2014-03-30}}</ref> A week-long series of rallies, exhibits, observances and performances occurred on the Mall from April 17 to April 25, 2010 to commemorate Earth Day's 40th anniversary.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=http://ww2.earthday.net/changetheclimaterally|title=Earth Day 2010 – The 40th Anniversary|publisher=[http://ww2.earthday.net/ Earth Day Network]|accessdate=2010-02-25}}<br>(2) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6OSzWic6p|archivedate=2014-03-30|url=http://www.earthday.org/earth-day-history-movement|title=Earth Day: The History of A Movement|work=[http://www.earthday.org/about-earth-day-network About Earth Day Network]|publisher=[http://www.earthday.org/ Earth Day Network]|accessdate=2014-03-30}}</ref> The final day's events featured performances by [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Mavis Staples]], [[The Roots]], [[John Legend]], [[Jimmy Cliff]] and others.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/04/25/AR2010042503324.html|last=Richards|first=Chris|title=Earth Day Climate Rally features music, speeches and an assist from Mother Nature|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|publisher=[http://www.washingtonpost.com The Washington Post Company, Washington, D.C.]|page=C.1|date=2010-04-26|accessdate=2010-04-26}}</ref> The 2012 Earth Day rally, which featured music, entertainment, celebrity speakers and environmental activities, took place on the Mall during a rainy day on Sunday, April 22.  [[Cheap Trick]], [[Dave Mason]], Kicking Daisies and The Explorers Club performed and Congressmen [[John Dingell]] and [[Edward Markey]] spoke.<ref>(1) {{cite web|last=Cooper|first=Rachel|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/671sQwVg7|archivedate=2012-04-18|url=http://dc.about.com/od/specialevents/a/EarthDayMall.htm|title=Earth Day 2012 on the National Mall: Rally for the Green Generation|work=[http://dc.about.com About.com Washington, DC.]|publisher=[[About.com]]|accessdate=2012-04-18}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Bahrampour|first=Tara|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/rains-dont-water-down-earth-day-enthusiasm/2012/04/22/gIQAQ1FjaT_story.html|title=Rains don’t water down Earth Day enthusiasm|date=2012-04-22|work=[http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/ Post Local]|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=2012-05-04}}</ref> In 2013, an "Earth Month" at Washington's [[Union Station (Washington, D.C.)|Union Station]] replaced the Mall's Earth Day event.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cooper|first=Rachel|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6OSohQhgH|archivedate=2014-03-30|url=http://dc.about.com/od/specialevents/a/EarthDayMall.htm|title=Earth Day 2013 on the National Mall: Rally for the Green Generation|work=[http://dc.about.com About.com Washington, DC.]|publisher=[[About.com]]|accessdate=2014-03-30}}</ref>  On April 19, 2015, a "[[Global citizenship|Global Citizen]]" Earth Day concert featured performances on the Washington Monument grounds by [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]], [[My Morning Jacket]], [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Train (band)|
Train]] and [[No Doubt]].<ref>(1) {{cite web|first=Shannon|last=Carlin|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20150316214440/http://radio.com/2015/03/05/global-citizen-2015-earth-day-concert-no-doubt-fall-out-boy|archivedate=2015-03-16|url=http://radio.com/2015/03/05/global-citizen-2015-earth-day-concert-no-doubt-fall-out-boy/|title=No Doubt, Fall Out Boy, Usher to Perform at Global Citizen 2015 Earth Day Concert|publisher=[http://radio.com/ radio.com]|accessdate=2015-03-16}}<br>(2) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6XtbWvXmG|archivedate=2015-04-18|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/express/wp/2015/04/16/what-you-need-to-know-about-saturdays-global-citizen-2015-earth-day-rally-on-the-national-mall|date=2015-03-05||title=What you need to know about Saturday’s Global Citizen 2015 Earth Day rally on the National Mall|first=Rudi |last=Greenberg|date=2015-04-16|work=[http://www.washingtonpost.com/express/ Express]|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=2015-04-18}}</ref> 

The [[National Symphony Orchestra (United States)|National Symphony Orchestra]] presents each year its ''[[National Memorial Day Concert]]'' on the west lawn of the United States Capitol during the evening of the Sunday before [[Memorial Day]] (the last Monday of May).<ref>(1) {{cite web |url=http://www.kennedy-center.org/events/?event=NMMEM|title=National Memorial Day Concert|publisher=[http://www.kennedy-center.org The John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, Washington, D.C.]|accessdate=2012-05-24}}<br>(2) {{cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/memorialdayconcert|title=National Memorial Day Concert|publisher=[http://www.pbs.org Public Broadcasting Service (PBS)]|accessdate=2011-05-11}}</ref> The National Gallery of Art hosts a ''Jazz in the Garden'' series each year in the museum's Sculpture Garden on Friday evenings from late May through August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nga.gov/programs/jazz|title=Jazz in the Garden|publisher=[[National Gallery of Art]]|accessdate=2010-04-26}}</ref>

Components of the [[United States Navy Band]], the [[United States Air Force Band]], the [[United States Marine Band]] and the [[United States Army Band]] perform on the west steps of the United States Capitol on Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday evenings, respectively, during June, July and August.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=http://www.navyband.navy.mil/summer_concert_series.shtml|title=Summer Concert Series|publisher=[http://www.navyband.navy.mil/ The United States Navy Band]|accessdate=2011-05-11}}<br>(2) {{cite web|url=http://www.navyband.navy.mil/sched.shtml|title=Performance schedule for The United States Navy Band for the Washington D.C. metro area, July and August, 2007|publisher=[http://www.navyband.navy.mil/ The United States Navy Band]|accessdate=2010-10-27 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070630044031/http://www.navyband.navy.mil/sched.shtml |archivedate = 2007-06-30}}<br>(3){{cite web|url=http://www.navyband.navy.mil/CBsched.shtml|title=The United States Navy Band Performance Schedule, August 2007|publisher=[http://www.navyband.navy.mil/ The United States Navy Band]|accessdate=2010-10-27|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070817080048/www.navyband.navy.mil/CBsched.shtml|archivedate=2007-08-17}}<br>(4) {{cite web|url=http://www.usafband.af.mil/events/index.asp|title=The United States Air Force Band events|publisher=[http://www.usafband.af.mil/ The United States Air Force Band]|accessdate=2010-05-07}}<br>(5) {{cite web|url=http://www.usarmyband.com/event-calendar.html|title=Event Calendar|publisher=[http://www.usarmyband.com The United States Army Band “Pershing's Own”]|accessdate=2010-03-01}}<br>(6) {{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/ncro/publicaffairs/summerinthecity.htm|title=2012 Summer Concert Series|publisher=[http://www.nps.gov/ncro/ National Capital Regional Office, National Park Service]|date=2012-01-09|accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref><ref name="Marine Band">{{cite web|url=http://www.marineband.usmc.mil/calendar/index.asp|title=Calendar|publisher=[http://www.marineband.usmc.mil/ The United States Marine Band "The President's Own"]|accessdate=2010-06-18}}</ref> The Marine Band repeats each Wednesday Capitol performance on the following evening (Thursday) at the Sylvan Theater on the grounds of the Washington Monument.<ref name="Marine Band" /> Components of U.S. military bands also provide evening concerts at the World War II Memorial from May through August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwiimemorialfriends.org/news.php?st=sid9|title=Free 2011 Summer Concert Series Schedule|publisher=[http://www.wwiimemorialfriends.org/ Friends of the National World War II Memorial]|accessdate=2011-07-19}}</ref>

The [[Smithsonian Folklife Festival]] takes place on the Mall each year for two weeks around [[Independence Day (United States)|Independence Day]] (July 4).<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=http://www.festival.si.edu|title=Smithsonian Folklife Festival|publisher=[http://www.si.edu/ Smithsonian Institution, Washington, D.C.]|accessdate=2009-11-05}}<br>(2) {{cite web|url=http://www.festival.si.edu/past_festivals/year.aspx|title=Smithsonian Folklife Festival: Programs by Year|publisher=[http://www.si.edu/ Smithsonian Institution, Washington, D.C.]|accessdate=2010-04-13}}</ref> On that holiday, the ''[[A Capitol Fourth]]'' concert takes place in the late afternoon and early evening on the west lawn of the Capitol.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/capitolfourth|title=A Capitol Fourth|publisher=[http://www.pbs.org/ Public Broadcasting System (PBS)]|accessdate=2009-11-05}}</ref>  This and other Independence Day celebrations on and near the Mall end after sunset with a [[fireworks]] display between the Washington Monument and the Lincoln Memorial.<ref>(1) {{cite web|last=Cooper|first=Rachel|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/67vgautzO|archivedate=2012-05-25|url=http://dc.about.com/od/specialevents/a/4thofJuly.htm|title=Fourth of July Fireworks 2012 in Washington DC|work=[http://dc.about.com/od/touristattractions/u/Thingstodo.htm Things to Do in the Washington DC/Capital Region]|publisher=[http://about.com About.com, a part of The New York Times Company]|accessdate=2012-05-25}}<br>(2) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/67vhsmpRB|archivedate=2012-05-25|url=http://www.nps.gov/foju/thingstodo.htm|title=Things to Do|work=[http://www.nps.gov/foju/index.htm Fourth of July at the National Mall]|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|date=2012-05-24|accessdate=2012-05-25}}<br>(3) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/67vkIkI1z|archivedate=2012-05-25|url=http://www.nps.gov/foju/fireworks.htm|title=Fireworks|work=[http://www.nps.gov/foju/index.htm Fourth of July at the National Mall]|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|date=2012-05-20|accessdate=2012-05-25}}</ref> On Monday nights during July and August, the annual [[Screen on the Green (Washington, D.C.)|Screen on the Green]] movie festival takes place on the Mall between 4th and 7th Streets.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cooper|first=Rachel|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110707075105/http://dc.about.com/od/specialevents/a/Screengreen.htm|archivedate=2011-07-07|url=http://dc.about.com/od/specialevents/a/Screengreen.htm|title=Screen on the Green 2011 in Washington DC: Free Outdoor Movies at the National Mall|publisher=[http://about.com About.com, a part of The New York Times Company]|accessdate=2011-05-11}}</ref> The free classic movies are projected on large portable screens and typically draw crowds of thousands of people.

The National Symphony Orchestra presents each year its ''Labor Day Capitol Concert'' on the west lawn of the United States Capitol during the evening of the Sunday before [[Labor Day]] (the first Monday of September).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kennedy-center.org/events/?event=NMLAB|title=National Symphony Orchestra: Labor Day Capitol Concert 2012|publisher=[http://www.kennedy-center.org The John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts, Washington, D.C.]|accessdate=2012-08-24}}</ref>

[[File:MarianAndersonLincolnMemorial.png||thumb|337px|The 1939 concert by Marian Anderson, facing east from the Lincoln Memorial]]

====Other events====
On April 9, 1939, singer [[Marian Anderson]] gave an [[Easter]] Sunday concert at the Lincoln Memorial after the [[Daughters of the American Revolution]] (DAR) denied a request by [[Howard University]] for her to give an Easter performance at the DAR's nearby [[Racial segregation in the United States|racially segregated]] [[DAR Constitution Hall|Constitution Hall]] (see: [[Marian Anderson#1939 Lincoln Memorial concert]]). The event, which 75,000 people attended, occurred after President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] gave his assent for the performance.<ref>(1) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6JMrDTFdg|archivedate=2013-09-03|url=http://www.fdrlibrary.marist.edu/aboutfdr/anderson.html|title=Eleanor Roosevelt and Marian Anderson|publisher=[[Franklin D. Roosevelt Presidential Library and Museum]]|accessdate=2013-09-03}}<br>(2) {{cite book|last=Arsenault|first=Raymond|title=The Sound of Freedom: Marian Anderson, the Lincoln Memorial, and the Concert that Awakened America|location=New York|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury Press]]|year=2009|isbn=9781596915787}}</ref>

On Sunday, October 9, 1979, [[Pope John Paul II]] celebrated [[Mass (liturgy)|Mass]] on the National Mall during a visit to Washington.<ref>{{cite news|author=[[Associated Press]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103070813/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/religion/2008-03-29-papal-visit_N.htm|archivedate=2012-11-03|url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/religion/2008-03-29-papal-visit_N.htm|title=Public likely to see less of Pope Benedict than John Paul|work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=USA Today, a division of [[Gannett Co.]], Inc.|date=2008-03-29|accessdate=2015-01-03}}</ref> The celebration took place after an [[appellate court]] denied a motion for an [[injunction]] that [[atheist]]s [[Madalyn Murray O'Hair]] and [[Jon Garth Murray]] had filed to prevent the event from occurring.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150103193726/https://law.resource.org/pub/us/case/reporter/F2/613/613.F2d.931.79-2170.html|archivedate=2015-01-03|url=https://law.resource.org/pub/us/case/reporter/F2/613/613.F2d.931.79-2170.html|title=613 F.2d 931: 198 U.S.App.D.C. 198: Madalyn Murray O'HAIR and Jon Garth Murray, Appellants, v. Cecil ANDRUS, Secretary of the Interior, et al.: No. 79-2170: United States Court of Appeals, District of Columbia Circuit|publisher=[[Public.Resource.Org]]|date=1979-11-14|accessdate=2015-01-03}}</ref>

From 1980 through 1982, [[The Beach Boys]] and [[The Grass Roots]] performed Independence Day concerts on the Mall, attracting large crowds.<ref>{{cite news|title=July 4: Day of Music, Parades, Fireworks|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|publisher=[http://www.washingtonpost.com The Washington Post Company, Washington, D.C.]|date=1982-07-03|page=D1}}</ref><ref name=McCombs>(1) {{cite news|last=McCombs|first=Phil|date=1983-04-06|title=Watt Outlaws Rock Music on Mall for July 4|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|publisher=[http://www.washingtonpost.com The Washington Post Company, Washington, D.C.]|page=A.1}}<br>(2) {{cite news|last=McCombs|first=Phil and Harrington, Richard|date=1983-04-07|title=Watt Sets Off Uproar with Music Ban|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|publisher=[http://www.washingtonpost.com The Washington Post Company, Washington, D.C.]|pages=A.1, A.17}}</ref> However, in April 1983, [[James G. Watt]], [[Presidency of Ronald Reagan|President Ronald Reagan]]'s [[United States Secretary of the Interior|Secretary of the Interior]], banned Independence Day concerts on the Mall by such groups.  Watt said that "[[rock band]]s" that had performed on the Mall on Independence Day in 1981 and 1982 had encouraged drug use and alcoholism and had attracted "the wrong element", who would [[robbery|mug]] individuals and families attending any similar events in the future.<ref name=McCombs/>  Watt then announced that [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]] crooner [[Wayne Newton]], a friend and supporter of President Reagan and a contributor to [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] political campaigns, would perform at the Mall's 1983 Independence Day celebration.<ref name=McCombs/><ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130117074349/http://www.newsmeat.com/celebrity_political_donations/Wayne_Newton.php|archivedate=2013-01-17|url=http://www.newsmeat.com/celebrity_political_donations/Wayne_Newton.php|title=Campaign contributions of Wayne Newton|date=2012-01-16|publisher=NEWSMEAT by Polity Media, Inc.|accessdate=2015-03-04}}</ref>

During the ensuing uproar, [[Rob Grill]], lead singer of The Grass Roots, stated that he felt "highly insulted" by Watt's remarks, which he called "nothing but un-American".<ref name=McCombs/> The Beach Boys stated that the [[Soviet Union]], which had invited them to perform in [[Leningrad]] in 1978, "obviously .... did not feel that the group attracted the wrong element".<ref name=McCombs/> [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[George H. W. Bush]] said of The Beach Boys, "They're my friends and I like their music".<ref name=McCombs/>  On July 3, 1983, thousands attended a heavily-policed "Rock Against Reagan" concert that the [[hardcore punk|hardcore punk rock]] band, [[Dead Kennedys]],  performed on the Mall in response to Watt's action.<ref>(1) {{cite web|last=Smith|first=R.J.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20021022023148/http://www.deadkennedysnews.com/art020100.htm|archivedate=2002-10-22|url=http://www.deadkennedysnews.com/art020100.htm|title=Punk Rock On Trial|work=Dead Kennedys News|date=2000-02-01|accessdate=2015-03-04|quote=It was surely the biggest show of Dead Kennedys' career, and Ronald Reagan made it all possible. In 1983, one of his cabinet members canceled a fourth of July Beach Boys concert on federal grounds in Washington, D.C., fearing the band would bring the wrong element to the capital. The move looked like crackbrained politics on every level -- the administration appeared painfully out of touch (banning the Beach Boys?), and the official who canned the show didn't even realize that the band was publicly down with the Reagans.<br>This was political theater of the absurd, and it was therefore a place where Dead Kennedys felt exceedingly at home. The San Francisco foursome took action, putting together a punk-rock festival on the Mall, the expanse of lawn stretching between the Washington Monument and the Capitol building. They were goading the government to try to stop them. Instead, thousands of punks filled the grounds that day, and skinny DKs frontman [[Jello Biafra]] greeted them by comparing the Monument to a giant hooded Klansman. As he jumped around like an insane marionette to their ornery punkability, government helicopters hovered over the stage and D.C. cops nervously patrolled the edge of the throng.}}<br>(2) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110223202239/http://sites.google.com/site/livedeadkennedys/1983/19830703|archivedate=2011-02-23|url=https://www.sites.google.com/site/livedeadkennedys/1983/19830703|title=1983-07-03 - Rock Against Reagan, National Mall, Washington, DC|work=Dead Kennedys Concert Guide|publisher=[[Google]]|accessdate=2015-03-04}}<br>(3) {{cite news|last=Richards|first=Chris|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/click-track/post/dave-grohl-glancing-back-blasting-forward/2011/04/08/AFk5w02C_blog.html|title=Dave Grohl, glancing back, blasting forward|work=Click Track: The Washington Post Pop Music Blog|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2011-04-08|accessdate=2015-03-04|quote=On a family trip to Illinois in summer 1983, Grohl’s older cousin switched him on to punk rock — something that really clicked back home in July at a Dead Kennedys show on the National Mall. “There were cops on horses beating the [expletive] out of people. There were police helicopters.}}</ref> When Newton entered an Independence Day stage on the Mall on July 4, members of his audience [[booing|booed]].<ref name="Gettysburg">{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=soE0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=AegFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2280,5284705&hl=en|first=Tim (Associated Press)|last=Ahern|title=Newton concert goes off despite rain|work=Gettysburg Times|publisher=[http://www.gettysburgtimes.com Gettysburg Times, 1570 Fairfield Rd., Gettysburg, Pennsylvania]|page=7|date=1983-07-05|accessdate=2010-02-18}}</ref><ref>(1) {{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SdcxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=muMFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3000,2778153&hl=en|title=Newton Performance Dampened by Rain|last=Associated Press|work=[http://readingeagle.com/ Reading Eagle]|publisher=Reading Eagle Company, 345 Penn Street, Reading, Pennsylvania|page=27|date=1983-07-05|accessdate=2010-02-18}}<br>(2) {{cite web|first=John|last=Katsilometes|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20091101124433/http://www.lasvegassun.com/blogs/kats-report/2009/oct/30/newtons-recounting-1983-show-national-mall-telling/|archivedate=2009-11-01|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/blogs/kats-report/2009/oct/30/newtons-recounting-1983-show-national-mall-telling|title=Newton’s recounting of Beach Boys controversy a telling moment in ‘Once Before I Go’|work=The Kats Report|publisher=[http://www.lasvegassun.com Las Vegas Sun]|date=2009-10-30|accessdate=2015-02-04}}</ref> Watt apologized to The Beach Boys, [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Nancy Reagan]] apologized for Watt, and in 1984 The Beach Boys gave an Independence Day concert on the Mall to an audience of 750,000 people.<ref name="Gettysburg" /><ref>(1) {{cite web|url=http://thebeachboys.com/timeline.aspx|title=Timeline|publisher=The Beach Boys (Capitol Records)|accessdate=2010-01-29}}<br>(2) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20081204112554/http://www.yuddy.com/celebrity/the-beach-boys/bio|archivedate=2008-12-04|url=http://www.yuddy.com/celebrity/the-beach-boys/bio|title=The Beach Boys Bio|publisher=Yuddy, LLC. © and TM Yuddy, LLC|accessdate=2012-04-19}}<br>(3) {{cite news|first=Richard|last=Harrington|title=Back to the Beach Boys: Rock Returns to Mall For the Fourth of July; Beach Boys to Perform On the Mall July 4|work=[[The Washington Post|The&nbsp;Washington Post]]|publisher=[http://www.washingtonpost.com The Washington Post Company, Washington, D.C.]|page=B.1|date=1984-06-06}}</ref>

[[Image:Britney Spears Navy.jpg|thumb|left|225px|Britney Spears performs during the "NFL Kickoff Live from the National Mall Presented by Pepsi Vanilla" concert, September 4, 2003.]]
On September 4, 2003, [[Britney Spears]], [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Aerosmith]] and others performed in a nationally-televised "NFL Kickoff Live from the National Mall Presented by Pepsi Vanilla" (see [[National Football League Kickoff game#Pre-game concerts]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20030805005482/en/|title='NFL Kickoff Live from the National Mall' Presented by Pepsi Vanilla Featuring Aerosmith, Mary J. Blige, Aretha Franklin, Britney Spears and Others Thursday, September 4|publisher=[[Business Wire]]|date=2003-08-05|location=New York|accessdate=2012-03-15}}</ref> Preceded by a three-day [[National Football League]] "interactive [[Super Bowl]] theme park", the event had primarily commercial purposes, unlike earlier major activities on the Mall. Three weeks later, the [[United States Senate]] overwhelmingly passed legislation that, when enacted into law, limited displays of commercial sponsorship on the Mall.<ref>(1) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6DHOdd4uA|archivedate=2012-12-29|url=http://www.savethemall.org/updates/20030923.html|title=Message concerning passage of Senate amendment to HR2691, 108th United States Congress|publisher=[http://www.savethemall.org/ National Coalition to Save Our Mall Inc.]|date=2003-09-24|accessdate=2012-12-29}}<br>(2) {{cite book|chapter-url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/PLAW-108publ108/pdf/PLAW-108publ108.pdf|format=pdf|title=[[Act of Congress|Public Law]] 108-108: Department of the Interior and Related Agencies Appropriations Act, 2004|date=2003-11-10|chapter=Sec. 145|pages=117 Stat. 1280 - 117 Stat. 1281|publisher=[[United States Government Printing Office]]|location=Washington, D.C.|accessdate=2012-12-29|quote=SEC. 145. None of the funds appropriated or otherwise made available by this or any other Act, hereafter enacted, may be used to permit the use of the National Mall for a special event, unless the permit expressly prohibits the erection, placement, or use of structures and signs bearing commercial advertising. The Secretary may allow for recognition of sponsors of special events: Provided, That the size and form of the recognition shall be consistent with the special nature and sanctity of the Mall and any lettering or design identifying the sponsor shall be no larger than one-third the size of the lettering or design identifying the special event. In approving special events, the Secretary shall ensure, to the maximum extent practicable, that public use of, and access to the Mall is not restricted. For purposes of this section, the term ‘‘special event’’ shall have the meaning given to it by section 7.96(g)(1)(ii) of title 36, Code of Federal Regulations.}}</ref>

On July 7, 2007, one leg of [[Live Earth concert, Washington, D.C.|Live Earth]] was held outdoors at the National Museum of the American Indian on the Mall.  Former [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Al Gore]] presented, and artists such as [[Garth Brooks]] and [[Trisha Yearwood]] performed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liveearth.org/en/press/pressrelease/live-earth-special-broadcast-event-washington-dc-announced-al-gore-attend-garth-b|title=Live Earth Special Broadcast Event in Washington, DC Announced -- Al Gore To Attend; Garth Brooks & Trisha Eastwood To Perform|date=2007-07-06|publisher=[http://liveearth.org Live Earth]|accessdate=2009-11-09}}</ref>

Occurring once every two to three years on the Mall in the early fall from 2002 to 2009,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solardecathlon.gov/history.cfm|title=Solar Decathlon History|work=[[United States Department of Energy|U.S. Department of Energy]] Solar Decathlon|publisher=[[National Renewable Energy Laboratory]]|date=2010-10-25|accessdate=2010-12-14}}</ref> the [[Solar Decathlon|U.S. Department of Energy Solar Decathlon]] displayed [[solar energy|solar-powered]] houses that competitive collegiate teams designed, constructed and operated.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100810100022/http://www.solardecathlon.gov/about.cfm|archivedate=2010-08-10|url=http://www.solardecathlon.gov/about.cfm|title=About Solar Decathlon|work=[[United States Department of Energy|U.S. Department of Energy]] Solar Decathlon|publisher=[[National Renewable Energy Laboratory]]|date=2010-05-07|accessdate=2013-01-27}}</ref><ref name=decathlon1>{{cite web|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110106203027/http://www.solardecathlon.gov/blog/archives/572|archivedate=2011-01-06|url=http://www.solardecathlon.gov/blog/archives/572|title=DOE Announces Dates for U.S. Department of Energy Solar Decathlon 2011|work=[http://www.solardecathlon.gov/blog Solar Decathlon News Blog]|publisher=[[United States Department of Energy]]|date=2010-09-23|accessdate=2011-09-12}}</ref> Igniting a controversy, the [[United States Department of Energy|Department of Energy]] (DOE) decided to move the 2011 Decathlon off the Mall, claiming that this would support an effort to protect, improve and restore the park.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solardecathlon.gov/blog/archives/629|title=Message Regarding the Location of the U.S. Department of Energy Solar Decathlon 2011|work=[http://www.solardecathlon.gov/blog Solar Decathlon News Blog]|publisher=[[United States Department of Energy]]|date=2011-01-11|accessdate=2011-01-18}}</ref> Federal officials stated that heavy equipment that had placed two-story houses on the Mall during earlier Decathlons had cracked walkways and killed grass to a greater extent than had most other Mall events.<ref name=Decathlon1>{{cite web|last=Fears|first=Darryl|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/02/12/AR2011021203215.html|title=Students' solar-energy showcase is kicked off Mall|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2011-02-12|accessdate=2011-02-15}}</ref> On February 4, 2011, a [[Washington Post]] editorial criticized attempts to have President Obama restore the event to the Mall.<ref>{{cite web|author=Editorial|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/02/04/AR2011020406593.html|title=Why the Solar Decathlon should forsake the Mall|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2011-02-04|accessdate=2011-02-07}}</ref>  Nevertheless, by February 12, 2011, at least thirteen [[Members of the 111th United States Congress|U.S. Senators]] had signed a letter asking the DOE to reconsider its decision.<ref name=Decathlon1 />  On February 23, 2011, the DOE and the Department of the Interior announced that the 2011 Solar Decathlon would take place along [[Ohio Drive (Washington, D.C.)|Ohio Drive]] southeast of the Franklin Delano Roosevelt Memorial in West Potomac Park.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=http://www.solardecathlon.gov/blog/archives/731|title=Energy, Interior Departments Announce New Location for Solar Decathlon 2011|work=[http://www.solardecathlon.gov/blog Solar Decathlon News Blog]|publisher=[[United States Department of Energy]]|date=2011-02-23|accessdate=2011-02-28}}<br>(2) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110304202236/http://www.solardecathlon.gov/pdfs/2011_map.pdf|archivedate=2011-03-04|url=http://www.solardecathlon.gov/pdfs/2011_map.pdf|title=Map: U.S. Department of Energy Solar Decathlon 2011: National Mall West Potomac Park|work=U.S. Department of Energy Solar Decathlon|publisher=[[National Renewable Energy Laboratory]]|date=2011-02-23|accessdate=2013-01-27}}<br>(3) {{cite web|last=Fears|first=Darryl|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/02/23/AR2011022307849.html|title=Solar Decathlon houses now have a home on the Mall|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2011-02-23|accessdate=2011-02-27}}</ref>  The event took place in the Park from September 23 through October 2, 2011.<ref name=decathlon1/><ref>{{cite web|last=Brown|first=Emma|last2=Eilperin|first2=Juliet|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post_now/post/u-md-watershed-home-wins-solar-decathlon/2011/10/01/gIQAvtZUDL_blog.html|title=U-Md. ‘WaterShed’ home wins Solar Decathlon|work=PostLocal|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2011-10-01|accessdate=2011-10-12}}</ref> The 2013 Solar Decathlon took place in [[California]] instead of Washington.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solardecathlon.gov/blog/archives/date/2013/10|title=Archive for October, 2013|work=U.S. Department of Energy  Solar Decathlon, [[Orange County Great Park]], [[Irvine, California]], October 3–13, 2013|date=2013-10-13|accessdate=2013-10-19}}</ref>

From 2003 to 2013, the [[National Book Festival]] took place on the Mall each year in late September or early October.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=http://www.loc.gov/today/pr/2003/03-133.html|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6MZy9VS2d|archivedate=2014-01-12|accessdate=2014-01-12|date=2003-03-14|title=2003 National Book Festival to be Held October 4 on the National Mall|work=[http://www.loc.gov/today/pr/2003/index.html News Releases: News from the Library of Congress]|publisher=Library of Congress}}<br>(2) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6MaBYPhMt|archivedate=2014-01-12|url=http://www.loc.gov/bookfest/information|title=Festival Information|work=[http://www.webcitation.org/6MZ9chfMr 2013 Library of Congress National Book Festival]|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|accessdate=2014-01-12}}</ref>  However, the event moved to the [[Walter E. Washington Convention Center]] in 2014 because the NPS became concerned about the damage that pedestrians had inflicted on the Mall's lawn during previous Festivals.<ref>(1) {{cite web|last=Charles|first=Ron|date=2014-01-08|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6MZAufCDT|archivedate=2014-01-12|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/national-book-festival-to-relocate-from-the-mall-to-the-dc-convention-center/2014/01/08/18327b12-78a2-11e3-8963-b4b654bcc9b2_story.html|title=National Book Festival to relocate from the Mall to the D.C. convention center|work=Style|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=2014-01-12}}<br>(2) {{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029024031/http://www.loc.gov/bookfest/|archivedate=2014-10-29|url=http://www.loc.gov/bookfest|title=Library of Congress National Book Festival|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|accessdate=2014-11-05}}</ref>

A four-day exhibition took place each year on the Mall during [[Partnership for Public Service#Public Service Recognition Week|Public Service Recognition Week]] (the first full week of May) until 2010.  Government agencies participating in the event sponsored exhibits that displayed the works of public employees and that enabled visitors to learn about government programs and initiatives, discuss employee benefits, and interact with agency representatives.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=http://opm.gov/psrw/|title=Public Service Recognition Week|publisher=[http://opm.gov/ U.S. Office of Personnel Management]|accessdate=2010-02-25}}<br>(2) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20100331200357/http://publicservicerecognitionweek.org/exhibitors/index.shtml|archivedate=2010-03-31|title=Public Service Recognition Week|publisher=[http://ourpublicservice.org/OPS/ Partnership for Public Service]|accessdate=2012-04-05|url=http://publicservicerecognitionweek.org/exhibitors/index.shtml}}</ref> However, the [[2011 United States federal budget]] ([[s:Public Law 112-10|Public Law 112-10]]), which was belatedly enacted on April 15, 2011, contained no funding for that year's event, forcing the event's cancellation.<ref>{{cite news|last=Harwood|first=Markie|url=http://www.federaltimes.com/article/20110421/PERSONNEL02/104210303|title=Public Service Recognition Week events on National Mall cancelled|work=[[Federal Times]]|publisher=[[Gannett]] Government Media Corporation|date=2011-04-21|accessdate=2012-04-05}}</ref>  The event did not take place in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/66jYgFywc|archivedate=2012-04-06|url=http://publicservicerecognitionweek.org/events/|title=2012 Events|work=Public Service Recognition Week: May 6–12|publisher=[http://ourpublicservice.org/OPS/ Partnership for Public Service]|accessdate=2012-04-06}}</ref>

[[File:Veterans Day concert on the National Mall photo D Ramey Logan.jpg|thumb|325px|Concert for Valor on the National Mall, November 11, 2014, looking west from the United States Capitol grounds.]]

On June 12, 2010, [[Tareq Salahi|Tareq]] and [[Michaele Salahi]], a couple under investigation for allegedly [[Gate-crashing|crashing]] a White House [[state dinner]] for the [[Prime Minister of India]] in November 2009 (see: [[2009 U.S. state dinner security breaches]]), hosted an [[America's Polo Cup]] match between the United States and [[India]] on the Mall. The advertised ticket price for this event was $95 per person.<ref name="Washington Post">{{cite news|last=Tucker|first=Neely|date=2010-06-13|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/12/AR2010061204092.html|title=White House crashers Tareq and Michaele Salahi hold polo event on the Mall|work=[[Washington Post]]|publisher=The Washington Post Company|location=Washington, D.C.|page=C.5|accessdate=2010-06-15}}</ref>  Reports of the event stated that the players who represented India were actually of [[Pakistan]]i origin and were from [[Florida]].<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=http://www.overoll.com/Content/White-House-crashers-Tareq-and-Michaele-Salahi-hold-polo-event-on-the-Mall-/2010/6/13/267201.news|title=White House crashers Tareq and Michaele Salahi hold polo event on the Mall|quote=Polo players representing India, who say they are actually of Pakistani origin and are from Florida, pose for a picture.|work=[http://www.overoll.com/Topic/Fashion/1/139.news Fashion]|publisher=[http://www.overoll.com/ OverOll.com]|date=2010-06-13|accessdate=2010-08-30}}<br>(2) {{cite web|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/pagesix/crashers_miss_the_old_days_8La0s8npgjiz4otx0RBteO?CMP=OTC-rss&FEEDNAME=|title=White House gatecrashers miss the 'old days'|work=[http://www.nypost.com New York Post]|publisher=NYP Holdings, Inc.|date=2010-08-17|accessdate=2010-08-30}}</ref> A spokesman for the [[Embassy of India, Washington, D.C.|Embassy of India]] stated that neither the Embassy nor the [[government of India]] had any association with the event.<ref name="Washington Post" />  The event's website reportedly identified an Indian company, [[Kingfisher (beer)|Kingfisher Beer]], as a sponsor.  However, Kingfishers' chief executive denied that the company had sponsored the event.<ref name="Washington Post" />  Yashpal Singh, the president and chief executive of [[Mendocino Brewing Company]], Kingfisher's parent company, stated, "We are not sponsoring this event and have informed the people managing this event of that, .... We have sent legal notices to this effect, and he keeps on advertising us as a sponsor. I don't know what world he's living in."<ref name="Washington Post" />

The inaugural [[USA Science and Engineering Festival|USA Science and Engineering Festival Expo]] took place on the National Mall and surrounding areas on October 23 and 24, 2010.  More than 1,500 free interactive exhibits reportedly drew about 500,000 people to the event,<ref>{{cite news|last=Tamura|first=Leslie|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/10/25/AR2010102502482.html|title=Festival on the Mall challenges young and old to think scientifically|work=[[The Washington Post]]|place=Washington, D.C.|publisher=The Washington Post Company|date=2010-10-25|accessdate=2010-10-27|quote=More than 1,500 free, interactive exhibits drew about 500,000 people to downtown Washington this weekend to learn about science, technology, engineering and math.}}</ref> which had over 75 performances.<ref name=expo>{{cite web|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20101021080637/http://www.usasciencefestival.org/2010festival/expo?|archivedate=2010-10-21|url=http://www.usasciencefestival.org/2010festival/expo?|title=Science & Engineering Festival: Grand Finale Expo- October 23 & 24, 2010, 10am-5:30pm, Washington DC US|accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref>  The second Expo took place on April 28–29, 2012, in the Walter E. Washington Convention Center.<ref>(1)  {{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/66jXruSIM|archivedate=2012-04-06|url=http://www.usasciencefestival.org/|title=Celebrate Science at the 2nd USA Science and Engineering Festival|work=USA Science & Engineering Festival|accessdate=2012-04-06}}<br>(2)  {{cite web|last=Stein|first=Ben P.|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/67xd1b2XP|archivedate=2012-05-26|url=http://inside-science.blogspot.com/2012/04/usa-science-engineering-festival.html|title=The USA Science & Engineering Festival|work=[http://inside-science.blogspot.com InsideScience Currents]|date=2012-04-27|accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref>

On [[Veterans Day]], November 11, 2014, [[Bruce Springsteen]], [[Eminem]], [[Rihanna]], [[Metallica]], [[Carrie Underwood]], [[Dave Grohl]], the [[Zac Brown Band]] and other pop entertainers performed on the Mall during a free evening [[The Concert for Valor|Concert for Valor]] honoring veterans and their families.  Attendance was in the hundreds of thousands, making it one of the biggest events on the Mall for the year.<ref>(1) {{cite news|last=Richards|first=Chris|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/springsteen-eminem-rihanna-and-more-to-perform-at-free-veterans-day-concert-in-dc/2014/10/02/97980e82-4a41-11e4-891d-713f052086a0_story.html|title=Springsteen, Eminem, Rihanna and more to perform at free Veterans Day concert in D.C.|work=[http://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/ Style]|date=2014-10-02|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=2014-11-05}}<br>(2) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6Trdj0bz2|archivedate=2014-11-05|url=http://connected.giveanhour.org/show/concert-for-valor/wiki|title=The Concert for Valor|work=[http://connected.giveanhour.org Give an Hour Connected]|publisher=[http://www.giveanhour.org/ Give an Hour]|accessdate=2014-11-05}}<br>(3) {{cite web|url=http://www.theconcertforvalor.com/|title=The Concert for Valor: Saluting American Veterans|publisher=[[Home Box Office]]|accessdate=2014-11-05}}<br>(4) {{cite news|last=Schwartzman|first=Paul|last2=Parks|first2=Miles|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6UAFnYbVT|archivedate=2014-11-18|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/road-closures-metro-changes-as-dc-prepares-for-free-concert-for-valor-on-mall/2014/11/11/b6cad9a6-69a4-11e4-9fb4-a622dae742a2_story.html|title=To honor veterans, Mall is the stage for a flag-waving night of patriotism, music|work=[http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/ Local]|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2014-11-11|accessdate=2014-11-18}}<br>(5) {{cite news|last=Richards|first=Chris|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/6UAHtP4Z7|archivedate=2014-11-18|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/2014/11/11/9ae0136a-69ee-11e4-9fb4-a622dae742a2_story.html|title=Concert for Valor review: For the troops on Veterans Day, rough-edged reverence on the Mall|work=[http://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/ Style]|date=2014-11-11|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=2014-11-18}}<br>(6) {{cite news|last=Plater|first=Roz|last2=Roussey|first2=Tom|last3=The [[Associated Press]]|archiveurl=http://www.wjla.com/articles/2014/11/-concert-for-valor-on-national-mall-draws-800-000-in-tribute-to-u-s-veterans-108935.html|archivedate=2014-11-18|url=http://www.wjla.com/articles/2014/11/-concert-for-valor-on-national-mall-draws-800-000-in-tribute-to-u-s-veterans-108935.html|title='Concert for Valor' on National Mall draws hundreds of thousands in tribute to Veterans|work=[http://www.wjla.com/entertainment/ Entertainment]|date=2014-11-11|publisher=[[NewsChannel 8 (cable channel)|NewsChannel 8]]|accessdate=2010-11-18}}</ref>

==National Mall Plan==
[[File:National Mall undergoing renovations.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Lincoln Memorial Reflecting Pool undergoing reconstruction in June 2011]]

From 2006 through 2010, the NPS conducted a public process that created a plan for the future of the National Mall.<ref name=Summary/><ref name=update>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107122616/http://www.nps.gov/nationalmallplan/Documents/FEIS/NAMA_Summary2010.pdf|archivedate=2012-11-07|url=http://www.nps.gov/nationalmallplan/National%20Mall%20Plan.html|title=Update on the National Mall Plan|work=[http://www.nps.gov/nationalmallplan/ Enriching Your American Experience: The National Mall Plan]|year=2010|publisher=[http://www.nps.gov National Park Service, U.S. Department of the Interior]|accessdate=2015-12-22}}</ref> On July 13, 2010, the NPS issued in the [[Federal Register]] a notice of availability of a final [[environmental impact statement]] (EIS) for the National Mall Plan.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nps.gov/nationalmallplan/FR%20Notices/75_FR_39969%20(Natl%20Mall%20EIS%20&%20Plan).pdf|title=Federal Register Notice: Availability of a Final Environmental Impact Statement for the National Mall Plan|last=O'Dell|first=Margaret (Regional Director, National Capital Region, National Park Service, U.S. Department of the Interior)|publisher=[[Government Printing Office]]. 75 FR 39969 (2010-07-13)|accessdate=2010-08-17}}</ref> The two-volume final EIS responded to comments and incorporated changes to a draft EIS for the Plan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Final National Mall Plan Documents|url=http://www.nps.gov/nationalmallplan/FEISdocs.html|work=[http://www.nps.gov/nationalmallplan/ Enriching Your American Experience: The National Mall Plan]|publisher=[[National Park Service]], [[United States Department of the Interior]]|accessdate=2010-06-23}}</ref> On November 9, 2010, the NPS and the Department of the Interior issued a [[Record of Decision]] (ROD) that completed the planning process.<ref name=update /><ref name=AP>{{cite news|author=[[Associated Press]]|url=http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=131195982|title=Salazar Signs Plan To Restore National Mall In DC|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=2010-11-09|accessdate=2010-11-10}}</ref><ref name=Post>{{cite web|last=Ruane|first=Michael E.|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/local-breaking-news/dc/plan-to-restore-transform-mall.html|title=Plan to restore, transform Mall signed|work=Post Now: The Breaking News Blog|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2010-11-09|accessdate=2010-11-10}}</ref><ref name=Examiner>{{cite news|last=Babay|first=Emily|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/local/Plan-to-revitalize-Mall-gets-official-go-ahead-1510600-107002123.html|title=$700 million plan to revitalize National Mall set in motion|publisher=[[The Washington Examiner]]|date=2010-11-09|accessdate=2010-11-10}}</ref> The ROD contains a summary of the selected alternative, which is the basis for the Plan, together with mitigation measures developed to minimize environmental harm; other alternatives considered; the basis for the decision in terms of planning objectives and the criteria used to develop the preferred alternative; a finding of no impairment of park resources and values; the environmentally preferable alternative; and the public and agency involvement.<ref name=ROD>(1)  {{cite web|author=[[Ken Salazar|Salazar, Ken]]; [[Jonathan Jarvis|Jarvis, Jonathan B.]]|url=http://www.nps.gov/nationalmallplan/Documents/FEIS/11-9-2010NAMA_FINALROD.pdf|title=Record of Decision: National Mall Plan/Environmental Impact Statement: National Mall, Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[National Park Service]], [[United States Department of the Interior]]|date=2010-11-09| accessdate=2010-11-10}}<br>(2) {{cite journal|last=Whitesell|first=Stephen E., Regional Director, National Capital Region, [[National Park Service]]|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/FR-2011-10-28/pdf/2011-27891.pdf|title=Record of Decision on the Final Environmental Impact Statement for the National Mall Plan, National Mall and Memorial Parks, Washington, DC|work=[[Federal Register]]|volume=76|number=209|pages=66960–66961|date=2011-10-28|accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref>

The Plan proposed a number of changes to the Mall.  The NPS would construct at the east end of the Mall a wide expanse of paved surface in Union Square to accommodate demonstrations and other events by reducing the size of the Capitol Reflecting Pool or by replacing the pool with a fountain or other small water feature.  Additional proposed changes included the replacement of the Sylvan Theater on the Washington Monument grounds with a facility containing offices, restaurants and restrooms.<ref name=Summary /><ref name=AP /><ref name=Post /><ref name=Examiner />

On December 2, 2010, the [[National Capital Planning Commission]] (NCPC) unanimously approved the final National Mall Plan at a public hearing.<ref name=NCPC>(1) {{citation|url=http://www.ncpc.gov/ncpc/Main(T2)/ProjectReview(Tr2)/CommissionArchive/CommissionActionsiframepages/Archive/2010/December2010Actions.html|title=National Mall Plan|work=Commission Actions|publisher=[[National Capital Planning Commission]]|id=File number 7060|date=2010-12-02|accessdate=2012-05-26}}<br>(2) {{citation|last=Young|first=Deborah B., Secretary to the National Capital PlanningCommission |url=http://www.ncpc.gov/DocumentDepot/Actions_Recommendations/2010Dec/National_Mall_Plan_Action_7060_December2010_.pdf|title=Commission Action: The National Mall: National Mall Plan; Washington, DC|publisher=[[National Capital Planning Commission]]|id=File number 7060|date=2010-12-02|accessdate=2012-05-26}}</ref> The NCPC's approval allowed the NPS to move forward with implementation of the Plan's recommendations.<ref name=update /><ref name=Examiner /><ref name=ROD /><ref name=NCPC /> On March 1, 2012, the NCPC discussed a proposal that would decrease the Mall's existing green space by widening and paving most of the north-south walkways that cross the Mall between Seventh and Fourteenth Streets and by replacing with gravel large areas of grass that are located near the [[Smithsonian (WMATA station)|Smithsonian Metro Station]] and the National Gallery of Art's Sculpture Garden.<ref>{{cite web|last=Farmer|first=Liz|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/66rFGtu21|archivedate=2012-04-11|url=http://washingtonexaminer.com/local/dc/2012/03/national-malls-grass-getting-trimmed-new-plan/328356|title=National Mall's grass getting trimmed in new plan|publisher=[[The Washington Examiner]]|date=2012-03-01|accessdate=2012-04-11}}</ref>

On September 8, 2011, the Trust for the National Mall<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalmall.org/|title=Trust for the National Mall|accessdate=2011-09-12}}</ref> and the NPS announced an open competition for a redesign of the spaces on the National Mall that Union Square, the Sylvan Theater grounds and the Constitution Gardens lake now occupy.<ref name="design competition">{{cite web|last=Trescott|first=Jacqueline|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/competition-invites-redesign-of-three-spaces-on-mall/2011/09/01/gIQAU3r2CK_story.html|title=Competition invites redesign of three spaces on Mall|work=[http://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/ Lifestyle]|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2011-09-08|accessdate=2011-09-12}}</ref>  Former [[First Lady of the United States]] [[Laura Bush]] agreed to be the honorary co-chair of a drive to raise funds for the three projects.<ref name="design competition"/>

On April 9, 2012, the Trust for the National Mall announced the ideas for the redesign of Union Square, the Sylvan Theater grounds and Constitution Gardens lake area that finalists in the competition had submitted. The Trust asked the public to submit [[Online and offline|online]] comments that the competition jury would consider when evaluating each design.<ref>(1) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/66r7G0bwa|archivedate=2012-04-12|url=http://www.nationalmall.org/design-competition/ideas|title=The Ideas|work=[http://www.nationalmall.org/design-competition/ National Mall Design Competition]|publisher=[http://www.nationalmall.org/ Trust for the National Mall]|date=2012-04-09|accessdate=2012-04-12}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Watson|first=Leon|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/66r7ZlNuS|archivedate=2012-04-12|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2127218/Designs-running-new-grand-plan-Americas-yard-released.html|title=DC's National Mall to get a makeover: Designs unveiled in competition to redesign America's 'front yard'|work=[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/index.html MailOnline]|publisher=[[Associated Newspapers]]|date=2012-04-09|accessdate=2012-04-12}}<br>(3) {{cite web|last=Diamonstein-Spielvogel|first=Barbaralee|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/66rDwK5lO|archivedate=2012-04-11|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/dr-barbaralee-diamonsteinspielvogel/national-mall-design-competition_b_1404405.html|title=Designing the Future of the National Mall|work=[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/the-blog/ The Blog]|publisher=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=2012-04-09|accessdate=2012-04-12}}</ref> The Trust announced the winners of the competition on May 2, 2012. Groundbreaking for the first project was expected to take place by 2014, with the first ribbon-cutting ceremony by 2016.<ref>(1) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/67PwaCBAZ|archivedate=2012-05-04|url=http://www.bustler.net/index.php/article/national_mall_design_competition_selects_the_three_winning_teams/|title=National Mall Design Competition Selects the Three Winning Teams|publisher=[http://www.bustler.net/ Bustler: Architecture Competitions, Events & News]|date=2012-05-03|accessdate=2012-05-04}}<br>(2) {{cite web|last=Welton|first=Michael|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/museums/mall-design-contest-winners-named/2012/05/02/gIQAAHIdxT_story.html|title=Mall design contest winners named to redo D.C. sites|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2012-05-02|accessdate=2012-05-04}}</ref>

==Transportation==
[[File:Smithsonian Station 2.jpg|thumb|right|287px|[[Smithsonian (WMATA station)|Smithsonian station]] on the [[Washington Metro]], pictured in 2005]]
{{See also|Transportation in Washington, D.C.}}

===Public transportation===
The National Mall is accessible via the [[Washington Metro]], with the [[Smithsonian (WMATA station)|Smithsonian station]] located on the south side of the Mall, near the Smithsonian Institution Building between the Washington Monument and the United States Capitol.<ref>(1) {{cite web|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/66yhp8TiX|archivedate=2012-04-16|url=http://www.nps.gov/nama/planyourvisit/publictransportation.htm|title=Public Transportation|work=[http://www.nps.gov/nacc/index.htm National Mall, District of Columbia]|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|accessdate=2012-04-16}}<br>(2) {{cite web|url=http://www.wmata.com/rail/station_detail.cfm?station_id=54|title=Smithsonian Station|publisher=[[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]]|accessdate=2010-03-12}}</ref> The [[Federal Triangle (WMATA station)|Federal Triangle]], [[Archives (WMATA station)|Archives]], and [[Union Station (WMATA station)|Union Station]] Metro stations are also located near the Mall, to the north.<ref>(1) [http://www.wmata.com/rail/station_detail.cfm?station_id=53 Federal Triangle Station] ''in'' website of the [http://www.wmata.com Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]. Retrieved 2020-03-12.<br>(2){{cite web|url=http://www.wmata.com/rail/station_detail.cfm?station_id=81|title=Archives–Navy Memorial–Penn Quarter Station|publisher=[[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]]|accessdate=2010-03-12}}<br>(3) {{cite web|url=http://www.wmata.com/rail/station_detail.cfm?station_id=25|title=Union Station|publisher=[[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]]|accessdate=2010-03-12}}</ref> The [[L'Enfant Plaza (WMATA station)|L'Enfant Plaza]], [[Federal Center SW (WMATA station)|Federal Center Southwest]] and [[Capitol South (WMATA station)|Capitol South]] Metro stations are located several blocks south of the Mall.<ref>(1) {{cite web|url=http://www.wmata.com/rail/station_detail.cfm?station_id=82|title=L'Enfant Plaza Station|publisher=[[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]]|accessdate=21 December 2014}}<br>(2) {{cite web|url=http://www.wmata.com/rail/station_detail.cfm?station_id=58|title=Federal Center SW Station|publisher=[[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]]|accessdate=2010-03-12}}<br>(3) {{cite web|url=http://www.wmata.com/rail/station_detail.cfm?station_id=59|title=Capitol South Station|publisher=[[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]]|accessdate=2010-03-12}}</ref> [[Metrobus (Washington, D.C.)|Metrobus]] and the [[DC Circulator]] make scheduled stops near the Mall.<ref>(1){{cite web|url=http://www.wmata.com/pdfs/bus/DC.pdf|title=Map of Central Washington, DC, Area|work=Metrobus Route Map: Washington, DC|publisher=[[Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority]]|accessdate=2010-03-12}}<br>(2){{cite web|url=http://www.dccirculator.com/Home/BusRoutesandSchedules/CirculatorRouteMap.aspx|title=Circulator Route Map|publisher=[[DC Circulator]]|accessdate=2012-04-06}}</ref>

===Bicycles===
The NPS provides parking facilities for [[bicycle]]s near each of the major memorials as well as along the National Mall.<ref name=bicycle>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/nama/planyourvisit/bicyclinginformation.htm|title=Bicycling Information for National Mall|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|accessdate=2010-03-12}}</ref> From March to October, an NPS concessionaire rents out bicycles at the Thompson Boat Center, located near the intersection of [[Virginia Avenue]] NW and [[Rock Creek and Potomac Parkway]], {{convert|1|mi|km}} north of the Lincoln Memorial along the Potomac River-Rock Creek Trail.<ref name=bicycle /><ref>(1) {{cite web|url=http://www.thompsonboatcenter.com/bikerent.htm|title=Bicycle Rentals at Thompson Boat Center|publisher=[http://www.thompsonboatcenter.com/ Thompson Boat Center]|accessdate=2010-03-12}}<br>(2) Coordinates of Thompson Boat Center: {{Coord|38.9003057|-77.0580733|region:US-DC_type:landmark|name=Thompson Boat Center}}</ref>  The first two of five approved [[Capital Bikeshare]] stations opened on the National Mall on March 16, 2012, shortly before the start of the 2012 National Cherry Blossom Festival.<ref>{{cite news|first=Mark|last=Berman|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/dr-gridlock/post/capital-bikeshare-stations-open-on-the-mall/2012/03/16/gIQA5uAlGS_blog.html|title=Capital Bikeshare stations open on the Mall|work=Post Local: Dr. Gridlock|publisher=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2012-03-16|accessdate=2012-06-04}}</ref>

===Pedicabs===
The National Park Service licenses pedicab drivers to provide transportation and tours of the National Mall through its Commercial Use Authorization program.  There are 10 pedicab stands on the National Mall located in front of major Smithsonian museums and the national memorials.  

===Motor vehicle parking===
General visitor parking is available along Ohio Drive SW, between the Lincoln and Thomas Jefferson Memorials. Bus parking is available primarily along Ohio Drive, SW, near the Lincoln and Thomas Jefferson Memorials and along Ohio Drive SW, in [[East Potomac Park]]. There is limited handicapped parking at the Franklin Delano Roosevelt and World War II Memorials and near the Washington Monument and the Thomas Jefferson, Lincoln, Korean War Veterans, and Vietnam Veterans Memorials; otherwise, parking is extremely scarce in and near the Mall.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/mall/planyourvisit/directions.htm|title=Parking for National Mall|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|accessdate=2010-03-12}}</ref>

